nt for propofol and drug abuse indicated a reduction of midazolam use by 5.41 mg/day in the presence of clonidine (P = 0.05). Similar adjustments for the study groups and propofol use showed a reduction of midazolam by 7.9 mg/day (P=0.008) in patients with no history of drug abuse. Adjusting for clonidine and history of drug abuse did not indicate any significant effect of propofol on midazolam use (P=0.07) (<xref ref-type="table" rid="T4">Table 4</xref>).</p><table-wrap id="T4" position="float"><label>Table 4</label><caption><p>Regression analysis for drug abuse effect and propofol on midazolam requirement</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th style=" color:#000000;" align="left" valign="middle" rowspan="2" colspan="1">
